Recursively visiting each node could do it: the following will result in a depth first search

    std::vector&lt;Node*&gt; BuildList(Node* root) {
        vector&lt;Node*&gt; nodes;

        if(root) {
            nodes.push_back(root);
            BuildList(root, nodes);
        }

        return nodes;
    }

    void BuildList(Node* node, std::vector&lt;Node*&gt; current) {
        if(node-&gt;next_node_type_a) {
            current.push_back(node-&gt;next_node_type_a);
            BuildList(node-&gt;next_node_type_a, current);
        }

        if(node-&gt;next_node_type_b) {
            current.push_back(node-&gt;next_node_type_b);
            BuildList(node-&gt;next_node_type_b, current);
        }
    }

Of course, this could fail if your nodes link back to themselves, so consider swapping out `std::vector` for a set type

The simplest solution is to use recursivity. Since the depth of a (balanced) binary tree is `O(ln(n))` you can safely assume you wont get a stack overflow.

    void apply(Node* n)
    {
        if (n == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        DoStuffWithNode(n);
        apply(n-&gt;node_left);
        apply(n-&gt;node_right);
    }

Recursion is the idiomatic way of iterating over a binary tree as demonstrated in the other answers, **but** if you require an iterative solution, you can use an additional data structure such as a [`std::queue`][1] to iteratively traverse all the nodes.

This is known as [Breadth First Search][2] and it&#39;s important to note that the order of traversal will be different than that of recursion, which is an implementation of [Depth First Search][3].

    std::queue&lt;Node*&gt; nodesToVisit;
    nodesToVisit.push(&amp;start);
        
    while (nodesToVisit.size()) 
    {
        Node* n = nodesToVisit.front();
        nodesToVisit.pop();
        std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;New node: &quot; &lt;&lt; n-&gt;value &lt;&lt; std::endl;
        if (n-&gt;node_left)
        {
            nodesToVisit.push(n-&gt;node_left);
        }
        if (n-&gt;node_right)
        {
            nodesToVisit.push(n-&gt;node_right);
        }
    }

The same approach will also work for non-binary trees, but requires additional code for handling cyclical graphs, such as keeping track of all visited nodes in a `std::set`.


  [1]: http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/queue/queue/
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search
  [3]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search

The data structure you are using is a [binary tree][1]. To traverse through your binary tree *without* recursion, use the [breadth-first][2] approach, which involves using a [queue][3] to hold each node and process it. 

Adding a *.discovered* value on the Node class will prevent processing any Node twice. Reset this discovered value after processing all Nodes if you want to reuse this function. Using this value is only necessary if you cannot gaurantee that any Node points to an ancestor Node or points to itself.

    #include &lt;iostream&gt; 
    #include &lt;queue&gt; 
    using namespace std;
    
    void BreadthFirst(Node start) {
        Queue&lt;Node&gt; Q;
        start.discovered = true;
        Q.push(start)
        while (!Q.isEmpty()) {
            Node n = Q.pop()
            cout &lt;&lt; n.value &lt;&lt; endl;
            if (n-&gt;next_node_type_a != null) {
                if(n-&gt;next_node_type_a.discovered == false) {
                    n-&gt;next_node_type_a.discovered = true;
                    Q.push(n-&gt;next_node_type_a);
                }
            }
            if (n-&gt;next_node_type_b != null) {
                if(n-&gt;next_node_type_b.discovered == false) {
                    n-&gt;next_node_type_b.discovered = true;
                    Q.push(n-&gt;next_node_type_b);
                }
            }
        }
    }


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_tree
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search
  [3]: http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/queue/queue/

